<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900723-0037</DOCNO><DOCID>900723-0037.</DOCID><HL>   South Carolina Lawmakers   Focus of Inquiry on Votes</HL><DATE>07/23/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12</SO><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   COLUMBIA, S.C. -- A federal grand jury here has subpoenaedthe financial records of all 170 of South Carolina's statelegislators as part of an investigation into a cash-for-votesscheme.   In a statement, the Federal Bureau of Investigation andthe Justice Department confirmed that they were investigating&quot;allegations of illegal conduct involving certain members ofthe South Carolina Legislature.&quot; They wouldn't elaborate,except to say the investigation would be thorough and wouldbe concluded as quickly as possible.</LP><TEXT>   However, one person familiar with the investigation saidthat it stems from the FBI's use of an undercover lobbyist tooffer legislators money in exchange for their votes. Thegrand jury subpoenaed financial records from the 124 staterepresentatives Wednesday, the individual said, andsubpoenaed records for the 46 state senators Friday.</TEXT></DOC>